43
00:02:10,524 --> 00:02:17,108
So I'm going to give you my top 10 tips for teaching public presentation to game students,

44
00:02:17,508 --> 00:02:23,611
which sometimes seems like an oxymoron, but I'm here to say it actually should be one of your

45
00:02:24,092 --> 00:02:26,233
top priorities for teaching game students.

46
00:02:26,613 --> 00:02:30,775
Number one, do it early and often, okay, from day one, even before day one.

47
00:02:31,356 --> 00:02:37,099
Make presentation a key component of your classes. This means maybe show and tell of games.

48
00:02:37,479 --> 00:02:43,803
It could mean presenting for one minute on the design process. It doesn't have to be a big presentation.

49
00:02:43,843 --> 00:02:48,666
It doesn't even have to be the final presentation. It could be every single day they come in your class.

50
00:02:48,686 --> 00:02:52,829
They have to stand up, even if it's just at their desk, and talk about what they did in the last,

51
00:02:53,329 --> 00:02:56,631
since the last class. Get them used to it. Get them comfortable with it.

52
00:02:57,934 --> 00:03:00,336
Create a culture of presenting.

53
00:03:01,737 --> 00:03:05,579
This is hard to achieve, but it comes down to valuing presentation.

54
00:03:05,599 --> 00:03:11,103
I mean, making that one of the number one skills to be able to succeed in your program.

55
00:03:11,663 --> 00:03:12,584
It could mean that

56
00:03:13,044 --> 00:03:18,807
A large proportion of their grade is even presentation skills, not just design skills.

57
00:03:19,808 --> 00:03:24,711
Have a formal workshop, bring in some trainers, people who are experts in presentation.

58
00:03:25,211 --> 00:03:27,112
Maybe you're not the expert, that's okay.

59
00:03:27,472 --> 00:03:31,815
Have someone come in, give training and tips on how to make a good presentation, how to

60
00:03:31,855 --> 00:03:34,636
construct a good argument, how to tell a story.

61
00:03:35,504 --> 00:03:40,131
really well, and then have your students practice the rest of the semester.

62
00:03:41,032 --> 00:03:46,199
Do lots and lots of low stakes exercises. Not everything has to be graded, okay? You

63
00:03:46,219 --> 00:03:51,146
could just give feedback and have lots of ungraded assignments.

64
00:03:52,107 --> 00:03:58,449
Get students used to getting feedback, getting used to being critiqued, critique each other, lots of peer critique.

65
00:03:59,029 --> 00:04:06,613
It also means you're giving detailed instruction, not just on game design and development, but on the presentation skills, right?

66
00:04:06,673 --> 00:04:13,235
How to build speeches for different audiences, how to deal with different styles, formats, language use.

67
00:04:15,357 --> 00:04:19,498
Have students practice in a lot of different places.

68
00:04:19,758 --> 00:04:20,779
Have them at their desk.

69
00:04:21,059 --> 00:04:22,539
Have them stand up in front of the class.

70
00:04:22,779 --> 00:04:26,300
Have them do presentations online via Skype.

71
00:04:26,501 --> 00:04:28,361
Have them do it in a game, Second Life.

72
00:04:28,981 --> 00:04:34,343
Make presentations a normal part of the every day practice.

73
00:04:34,924 --> 00:04:36,324
Present beyond the classroom.

74
00:04:36,364 --> 00:04:38,185
Have them stand in front of clients.

75
00:04:38,505 --> 00:04:41,126
Have them go and present at a conference.

76
00:04:42,438 --> 00:04:48,564
Create a conference at your university where they can present in a public forum.

77
00:04:49,445 --> 00:04:51,047
Have them come to GDC and present.

78
00:04:51,968 --> 00:04:57,794
Have them at a game jam present at the end of the game jam or a hackathon their ideas,

79
00:04:57,834 --> 00:04:58,955
their works in progress.

80
00:05:00,082 --> 00:05:04,564
So really important, make sure your students are comfortable.

81
00:05:05,625 --> 00:05:06,906
Make sure they're supported.

82
00:05:07,546 --> 00:05:10,948
Make sure they understand that presenting matters,

83
00:05:11,208 --> 00:05:14,630
but that they also matter and their comfort matters.

84
00:05:15,210 --> 00:05:17,412
Sometimes we think in our head that.

85
00:05:17,772 --> 00:05:22,655
Game students are not going to be very good at presenting, so let's just not push them in that way.

86
00:05:22,976 --> 00:05:28,440
But I have found that, except for maybe one or two students, most students really want this practice,

87
00:05:28,560 --> 00:05:31,582
and they need this practice to succeed in their futures.

88
00:05:32,443 --> 00:05:36,666
But push boundaries. Get them out of their comfort zones, too.

89
00:05:37,166 --> 00:05:40,729
Give them credit for failing, making mistakes.

90
00:05:41,710 --> 00:05:46,054
Okay? Get them to do things that are out of their normal every day.

91
00:05:46,395 --> 00:05:53,241
Take risks. Go on job interviews. Go to GDC. Go to places that maybe take them outside of their normal.

92
00:05:53,862 --> 00:05:54,002
And...

93
00:05:55,480 --> 00:06:05,944
Make them gain their confidence, because if they gain their confidence, that's going to influence every aspect of their work, their design work, and who they are as people.

94
00:06:07,224 --> 00:06:11,946
Iterate, iterate, iterate, just as you would with the game design, the development process.

95
00:06:12,226 --> 00:06:17,068
Do the same thing with presentations, make them practice, practice again, and revise and revise.

96
00:06:17,828 --> 00:06:21,770
Have them videotape themselves, watch it, and practice and revise it.

97
00:06:22,130 --> 00:06:26,352
Have them peer critique. Have them practice using different language.

98
00:06:27,112 --> 00:06:34,175
Have them put on silly costumes. Use crazy props. Use crazy music. Anything that gets

99
00:06:34,215 --> 00:06:39,137
them to feel comfortable and want to get up there and keep trying and learning and experimenting.

100
00:06:40,968 --> 00:06:43,550
Be transparent with how you do evaluate them.

101
00:06:43,951 --> 00:06:46,133
When you are giving them grades, be really clear

102
00:06:46,153 --> 00:06:49,696
about how you're grading them, what matters to you.

103
00:06:50,116 --> 00:06:53,580
Give them the rubrics up in front, beforehand.

104
00:06:54,120 --> 00:06:57,703
Have them see the feedback forms that they're going to be using.

105
00:07:01,325 --> 00:07:03,848
Focus on logic and story.

106
00:07:03,868 --> 00:07:06,690
Okay, so they need to be able to do presentations

107
00:07:06,710 --> 00:07:08,772
that are supported by evidence and data,

108
00:07:08,992 --> 00:07:11,034
but also tell a good story, right?

109
00:07:11,334 --> 00:07:14,937
You want them to be able to connect with their audience,

110
00:07:15,598 --> 00:07:18,740
to be able to care about their subject,

111
00:07:19,281 --> 00:07:21,803
to talk through their wins and their losses,

112
00:07:21,843 --> 00:07:23,504
their successes and their challenges,

113
00:07:23,845 --> 00:07:25,966
and to make people remember through story.

114
00:07:27,935 --> 00:07:31,739
And oh wait, I said top 10, but I have an 11th.

115
00:07:32,560 --> 00:07:33,942
There I am making a mistake.

116
00:07:34,503 --> 00:07:36,846
Show them that you make mistakes, okay?

117
00:07:37,797 --> 00:07:38,998
It's okay to make mistakes.

118
00:07:39,578 --> 00:07:42,681
Be the model of someone who can make mistakes

119
00:07:42,881 --> 00:07:44,482
and can grow from it, okay?

120
00:07:44,963 --> 00:07:48,946
And number 11 is, even though you may have some standards

121
00:07:49,026 --> 00:07:50,928
and some rubrics and some requirements,

122
00:07:51,328 --> 00:07:53,790
you want to value different styles

123
00:07:53,850 --> 00:07:55,972
and different perspectives, okay?

124
00:07:56,212 --> 00:07:58,134
There's obviously certain things that you wanna hit,

125
00:07:58,214 --> 00:07:59,655
like good eye contact.

126
00:08:00,624 --> 00:08:07,488
Telling stories, making people care, connecting with the audience, clear, articulate ideas,

127
00:08:07,508 --> 00:08:10,289
you know, positive attitude and enthusiasm.

128
00:08:10,549 --> 00:08:12,010
Yes, you want that, right?

129
00:08:12,570 --> 00:08:22,656
But you also want to value different ways of presenting and also be accepting and open

130
00:08:22,696 --> 00:08:26,018
because that's going to build trust with your students and that's going

131
00:08:26,038 --> 00:08:29,920
to make them more comfortable and confident to be able to present in front of you.

132
00:08:31,430 --> 00:08:37,114
Ultimately it's about building relationships, not only with your audience, but also with

133
00:08:37,154 --> 00:08:37,815
your students.

134
00:08:38,175 --> 00:08:44,379
Having a culture of presenting is going to have your students feel more part of your

135
00:08:44,419 --> 00:08:45,319
program, right?

136
00:08:45,339 --> 00:08:48,081
It's going to serve them on their own teams.

137
00:08:48,341 --> 00:08:50,463
It's going to serve them at college and beyond college.

138
