00:10:09,522 --> 00:10:14,788
only for you to find an abject horror that could have been prevented if only they'd taken

159
00:10:14,828 --> 00:10:22,497
an intro drawing class, then you may be a victim of Game Academia's art problem.

160
00:10:25,746 --> 00:10:28,387
So what do I mean by game academia has an art problem?

161
00:10:29,248 --> 00:10:31,969
I'm going to define it as the way our field

162
00:10:31,989 --> 00:10:34,450
de-emphasizes game-making disciplines

163
00:10:34,770 --> 00:10:36,951
descended from the arts in favor of others.

164
00:10:37,552 --> 00:10:40,353
Now, to be clear, I'm not talking about games

165
00:10:40,393 --> 00:10:42,774
that use the affordances of contemporary art

166
00:10:43,554 --> 00:10:44,675
to design interactivity,

167
00:10:45,956 --> 00:10:48,057
but rather acknowledging the lineage

168
00:10:48,117 --> 00:10:50,578
between game asset creation specialties

169
00:10:51,098 --> 00:10:53,159
and the historic fields they're descended from.

170
00:10:55,365 --> 00:10:57,285
So what are some of these disciplines?

171
00:10:57,925 --> 00:10:59,346
Looking through the keywords used

172
00:10:59,386 --> 00:11:02,127
in the Degra Online Library shows the dominance

173
00:11:02,227 --> 00:11:05,848
of serious games, learning, and game interactivity design

174
00:11:05,908 --> 00:11:06,888
as research topics.

175
00:11:08,228 --> 00:11:10,449
Likewise, there are large numbers of keywords

176
00:11:10,509 --> 00:11:12,910
derived from terms in the social sciences,

177
00:11:13,290 --> 00:11:15,791
cognitive development, and behavior studies.

178
00:11:17,711 --> 00:11:20,272
What you don't see are the same number of topics

179
00:11:20,312 --> 00:11:23,073
in areas like spatial design in games,

180
00:11:24,450 --> 00:11:29,792
sound design, visual arts, and even music.

181
00:11:31,612 --> 00:11:33,273
So the first part of our problem is

182
00:11:33,413 --> 00:11:36,094
there's a distinct preference towards serious games,

183
00:11:36,434 --> 00:11:40,276
social science research, and others that favor mechanics,

184
00:11:40,356 --> 00:11:42,736
but away from deeper understandings

185
00:11:42,836 --> 00:11:44,617
of the aesthetic qualities of games.

186
00:11:46,793 --> 00:11:51,556
The second part comes when you look at industry conferences like here at GDC, at the East

187
00:11:51,596 --> 00:11:56,719
Coast Game Conference, or any other professional conference with a game art or visual arts

188
00:11:56,799 --> 00:12:02,643
track. Talks at these conferences seem more related to graphics development than the visual

189
00:12:02,723 --> 00:12:10,487
arts. Sessions at GDC 2016 in the visual arts track, for example, had titles like HDR rendering

190
00:12:10,527 --> 00:12:11,268
and Lumberyard.

191
00:12:12,533 --> 00:12:18,137
Shaders 101, foundational shader concepts for technical artists and every MFA's favorite

192
00:12:18,737 --> 00:12:26,543
photogrammetry and Star Wars battlefront. Of the 77 scheduled sessions at GDC 2016 in

193
00:12:26,563 --> 00:12:33,108
the visual arts track, only eight cited techniques or concepts explicitly from the fine arts

194
00:12:33,148 --> 00:12:38,251
such as color theory or composition. So who cares? Why is this a problem?

195
00:12:39,419 --> 00:12:48,167
Many of these attitudes trickle down into academic game programs, appearing in class design, research questions, and the structure of development teams in these environments.

196
00:12:49,288 --> 00:12:56,174
In many programs, there's a bias towards software usage and technical art pipelines, and away from studying fine art principles.

197
00:12:57,517 --> 00:13:01,799
The dominant subjects in games research focus on the work of game mechanic designers, while

198
00:13:01,839 --> 00:13:07,984
putting artists, composers, and sound designers in utilitarian roles that de-incentivize them

199
00:13:08,304 --> 00:13:10,125
from being researchers in their own right.

200
00:13:11,566 --> 00:13:15,969
The underlying issue for all of these is that we view games as monolithic objects, rather

201
00:13:16,009 --> 00:13:19,011
than collections of works by collaborating professionals.

202
00:13:19,511 --> 00:13:23,534
And instead of evolving from this monolith, we keep banging our heads against it.

203
00:13:25,201 --> 00:13:27,783
So what can be some practical solutions to this?

204
00:13:28,663 --> 00:13:33,487
Well, there are many, many, many works, all very good.

205
00:13:33,527 --> 00:13:34,527
I love these books.

206
00:13:36,229 --> 00:13:38,150
Studying game mechanics or meditations

207
00:13:38,210 --> 00:13:39,111
on the nature of play,

208
00:13:39,571 --> 00:13:42,253
there are few academic investigations

209
00:13:42,293 --> 00:13:44,654
of things like art production or sound design.

210
00:13:45,867 --> 00:13:50,792
Given that many of these understudied disciplines are descended from established fields, there

211
00:13:50,832 --> 00:13:56,558
are chances for true impact if you can discover what lies in the mysterious region between

212
00:13:56,598 --> 00:13:57,479
games and the arts.

213
00:14:00,182 --> 00:14:04,046
While the use of techniques or references from the broader arts or media history is

214
00:14:04,086 --> 00:14:07,669
common in other fields, it's not commonplace in games quite yet.

215
00:14:09,525 --> 00:14:13,410
So remember the 2013 Deagra theme of defragging game studies?

216
