00:15:35,537 --> 00:15:36,598
in the Unreal Engine.

247
00:15:38,187 --> 00:15:41,208
Reinforce things like proportion and composition

248
00:15:41,248 --> 00:15:43,228
in Photoshop concept art courses.

249
00:15:44,989 --> 00:15:47,530
So already, these opportunities can lead us down

250
00:15:47,570 --> 00:15:50,911
a variety of paths of looking more deeply into games,

251
00:15:51,031 --> 00:15:52,132
past their mechanics.

252
00:15:53,952 --> 00:15:56,993
Because as many practicing game developers will tell you,

253
00:15:57,394 --> 00:15:59,915
games are not self-contained productions

254
00:15:59,975 --> 00:16:01,835
that consist only of interactivity.

255
00:16:03,600 --> 00:16:06,102
Anyone who's ever gone from consumer to creator

256
00:16:06,483 --> 00:16:09,465
will tell you that when they've tried to make even simple games,

257
00:16:09,986 --> 00:16:13,448
elements that they took for granted suddenly seemed very big and impressive.

258
00:16:15,250 --> 00:16:18,552
Sure, interactivity is one of the things that make games unique, but

259
00:16:19,093 --> 00:16:23,577
if fans can understand that games have component parts worthy of study and

260
00:16:23,617 --> 00:16:24,317
celebration,

261
00:16:24,818 --> 00:16:27,280
why can't we who study games professionally?

262
00:16:28,747 --> 00:16:34,070
I know that for me, some of my colleagues, and many of my students, the artistic aspects

263
00:16:34,130 --> 00:16:39,092
of games are what excited us, stuck with us over the years, and inspired us to make games

264
00:16:39,152 --> 00:16:39,872
our careers.

265
00:16:40,993 --> 00:16:45,515
And if given the chance, I think that meaningful collaboration with the arts may be the next

266
00:16:45,555 --> 00:16:47,356
great way to make and study games.

267
00:16:48,036 --> 00:16:48,336
Thank you.

268
00:16:58,087 --> 00:16:59,669
Great segue, I work at an art school.

269
00:17:01,553 --> 00:17:03,396
So, hi, my name is Emma Westacott.

270
00:17:03,416 --> 00:17:10,349
I am an associate professor at OCAD University, which is an art and design school in Toronto.

271
00:17:12,553 --> 00:17:26,040
I wanted to, well first of all I just want to, my pronouns are she and her, and I'm going to talk really briefly about some pedagogic approaches from feminism for the classroom.

272
00:17:26,680 --> 00:17:32,443
So, as a middle-aged white feminist academic, I have significant privilege and

273
00:17:34,083 --> 00:17:37,585
I'll argue that we all have lots of privilege, even being here in this room.

274
00:17:38,165 --> 00:17:44,749
So one of the challenges for me as an educator is to think about ways in which I can engage my privilege

275
00:17:45,069 --> 00:17:49,631
for my students and for the communities that I work with and for.

276
00:17:51,352 --> 00:17:55,774
I'm also here representing a Canadian network called Reefig,

277
00:17:56,014 --> 00:18:02,558
which is funded by the SSHRC and is invested in building diversity in game culture.

278
00:18:03,051 --> 00:18:05,213
education and the industry.

279
00:18:06,074 --> 00:18:10,919
So a lot of the work, I'm sort of standing on the shoulders of others, and actually there

280
00:18:10,939 --> 00:18:14,483
are colleagues who are also part of the network here in the room, so I'm sort of speaking

281
00:18:14,523 --> 00:18:17,206
on behalf of significant others.

282
00:18:17,226 --> 00:18:17,266
So

283
00:18:22,350 --> 00:18:28,501
Where I wanted to start was describing the work that's necessary as a sort of ecosystem.

284
00:18:28,902 --> 00:18:33,289
I think it's impossible to look at your classroom in an isolated sense.

285
00:18:36,467 --> 00:18:42,171
One of the things that we can do is look at common functions

286
00:18:42,771 --> 00:18:44,152
that can be shared across a range of different

287
00:18:44,172 --> 00:18:44,893
sort of like contexts.

288
00:18:44,933 --> 00:18:46,894
An example of that is an inclusivity statement.

289
00:18:46,914 --> 00:18:49,256
So in the same way that we can see the inclusivity statement

290
00:18:49,296 --> 00:18:52,298
as we walk into the sort of main hall of GDC,

291
00:18:52,558 --> 00:18:55,120
we can sort of issue and publish inclusivity statements.

292
00:18:56,301 --> 00:18:59,725
in our programs, in our classrooms and in our institutions.

293
00:19:00,006 --> 00:19:04,111
And what that does is it sets up a sort of contract or a set of expectations for students

294
00:19:04,131 --> 00:19:08,135
when they come into the classroom about what is and what isn't acceptable behavior.

295
00:19:08,556 --> 00:19:12,721
So the inclusivity statement we have at our institution.

296
00:19:13,305 --> 00:19:18,187
is developed with thanks to the Different Games Collective who generously developed

297
00:19:18,507 --> 00:19:22,750
and published their inclusivity statement as an open source resource.

298
00:19:23,070 --> 00:19:27,652
So it's available on Different Games for those of you who wish to use it in your classrooms

299
00:19:27,692 --> 00:19:33,395
and I'd strongly urge you to take advantage of all the work by the collective in doing

300
00:19:33,455 --> 00:19:34,095
so and using it.

301
00:19:35,263 --> 00:19:39,065
So the ecosystem that I'm going to talk about starts from the classroom really, but it sort

302
00:19:39,105 --> 00:19:44,647
of moves out and beyond because I don't think, as I said before, that you can isolate activity

303
00:19:44,807 --> 00:19:46,227
purely to sort of classrooms.

304
00:19:47,668 --> 00:19:52,710
So we inhabit the ecosystems that go beyond the walls of our institutions.

305
00:19:53,270 --> 00:19:58,292
I'm particularly lucky where I teach, being based in Toronto, because we have a really

306
00:19:58,432 --> 00:20:04,234
healthy local indie scene, AAA developers, and a much sort of like wider context of sort

307
00:20:04,254 --> 00:20:04,814
of production.

308
00:20:06,240 --> 00:20:13,929
But I wanted to start just really talking about some fairly basic practices that you can use in your classroom.

309
00:20:14,349 --> 00:20:19,255
So regardless of your course material, I would argue that you could use feminist approaches.

310
00:20:19,976 --> 00:20:22,920
So your content doesn't have to be explicitly feminist.

311
00:20:23,080 --> 00:20:25,763
Your class will benefit from engaging with some of these.

312
00:20:25,963 --> 00:20:28,084
So, I'm going to go through some sort of techniques, if you like.

313
00:20:28,124 --> 00:20:30,205
So, use non-gendered or female pronouns.

314
00:20:30,845 --> 00:20:37,467
I always name the player as she, and you'll notice that I use the word player, not gamer.

315
00:20:37,767 --> 00:20:39,628
Now, there's a very particular reason for that.

316
00:20:39,708 --> 00:20:44,650
I use player, not gamer, because of how the gamer identity is being tarnished by online violence,

317
00:20:45,150 --> 00:20:46,570
and I explain that to my students.

318
00:20:47,330 --> 00:20:50,732
I use she because I'm a female gamer, and we often don't hear that.

319
00:20:51,212 --> 00:20:51,352
So...

320
00:20:53,030 --> 00:20:58,732
The second part of thinking about how you place yourself in the classroom is to pick

321
00:20:58,812 --> 00:21:04,135
women, pick minority voices. Women tend to be written out of histories. I'm old enough

322
00:21:04,335 --> 00:21:09,417
to remember the strong, powerful female designers that were around in the 90s. I've read enough

323
00:21:09,477 --> 00:21:14,340
history to understand about Ada Lovelace and Grace Hopper. And so, you know, we do have

324
00:21:14,440 --> 00:21:18,802
female role models in our histories and it behoves us as sort of educators to make sure

325
00:21:18,822 --> 00:21:21,943
that they're taught. So we need to be aware of our histories.

326
00:21:23,512 --> 00:21:27,997
And that's not just historical figures, but it's current makers.

327
00:21:28,217 --> 00:21:34,644
So there's a rich history of both female and feminist makers, academics, critics, and players.

328
00:21:35,025 --> 00:21:37,447
So make sure that you use them in the materials.

329
00:21:37,487 --> 00:21:39,810
And I teach both game design and game studies.

330
00:21:40,334 --> 00:21:46,016
So I have access to a rich range of resources across both sort of areas and it's always

331
00:21:46,056 --> 00:21:50,939
worth spending some time looking at the resources that you're using, whether it's in a sort

332
00:21:50,959 --> 00:21:56,081
of a liberal studies class or an applied design class, in terms of enriching the resources

333
00:21:56,101 --> 00:21:57,462
that you're offering to your students.

334
00:21:58,517 --> 00:22:07,203
So encourage critical readings as well. It's an old feminist technique to read against the dominant narrative of a particular text.

335
00:22:07,283 --> 00:22:13,006
Encourage your students to play against the rhetoric of a particular game to try and find the edges and the holes.

336
00:22:13,246 --> 00:22:19,490
And it's something that players do anyway, right? So there's no reason why you can't explicitly centre on that.

337
00:22:19,870 --> 00:22:22,812
with in-class playings, out-of-class exercises.

338
00:22:23,753 --> 00:22:27,975
And that's part of how you start to build up a notion of sort of

339
00:22:28,716 --> 00:22:30,797
criticality amongst your students.

340
00:22:30,957 --> 00:22:33,499
I had a student about three years ago who just said,

341
00:22:33,539 --> 00:22:35,100
well that's just the way games are.

342
00:22:35,680 --> 00:22:38,182
And it's like, really? They're 30 years old.

343
00:22:38,202 --> 00:22:41,284
You know, they're not like anything for any particular...

344
00:22:41,425 --> 00:22:43,867
You know, they're not set in stone.

345
00:22:44,267 --> 00:22:46,449
They're amorphous and they evolve.

346
00:22:46,769 --> 00:22:49,931
They come from a particular sort of technological and commercial background,

347
00:22:49,971 --> 00:22:52,213
but there's no reason why we shouldn't be pushing

348
00:22:52,633 --> 00:22:54,655
for new, more open, more diverse futures.

349
00:22:55,095 --> 00:22:57,818
And I think that that's something which sort of starts in the classroom.

350
00:22:58,218 --> 00:23:02,161
So to backtrack, encourage critical readings or playings of the games.

351
00:23:02,641 --> 00:23:03,842
Talk to your students about...

352
00:23:05,729 --> 00:23:14,571
And the sort of second point of this really is that there is, okay, so there's no such

353
00:23:14,651 --> 00:23:17,152
thing as a mutual design decision.

354
00:23:17,772 --> 00:23:22,614
Decisions are made by people in places and time, and often there's very particular reasons

355
00:23:22,654 --> 00:23:23,854
for those design decisions.

356
00:23:24,254 --> 00:23:32,617
But spread that context and don't let your students assume that decisions have been made

357
00:23:32,817 --> 00:23:33,857
in the ether, right?

358
00:23:35,455 --> 00:23:41,237
So another methodology or technique or approach I use a lot in classrooms is to try and find

359
00:23:41,297 --> 00:23:46,220
ways of shifting out of the teacher-student hierarchy, which is so problematic in terms

360
00:23:46,520 --> 00:23:49,981
of setting up hierarchies in classrooms.

361
00:23:50,582 --> 00:23:56,744
And there's many fashionable terms for how you can shift around with that power dynamic,

362
00:23:56,864 --> 00:23:58,865
but encourage different forms.

363
00:23:59,146 --> 00:24:04,188
In some ways, I'm standing here talking to you, reproducing that power dynamic, but it's

364
00:24:04,949 --> 00:24:10,150
really much richer in the classroom to think about splitting groups, letting people speak

365
00:24:10,310 --> 00:24:15,452
about and talk about an area or a game they have a deep passion about and present that

366
00:24:15,512 --> 00:24:18,872
knowledge and that expertise in a much more sort of flattened hierarchy.

367
00:24:19,873 --> 00:24:24,874
The other thing which I think is really important is there's no one right way of making games.

368
00:24:25,594 --> 00:24:28,735
There's no one accepted language of game design.

369
00:24:29,111 --> 00:24:33,853
And talking about that and allowing and celebrating different types of starting points, both to

370
00:24:33,893 --> 00:24:38,334
game making and game criticism, is really important as a way of including and opening

371
00:24:38,375 --> 00:24:39,835
up to different types of voices.

372
00:24:41,536 --> 00:24:47,298
So to repeat, shift out of the expert-student hierarchy, acknowledge a multitude of approaches,

373
00:24:47,898 --> 00:24:52,480
and insist on notions of authorship, games are made by people in places and times.

374
00:24:53,100 --> 00:24:58,402
So these techniques are applicable in every classroom, not just the feminist classroom.

375
00:25:00,718 --> 00:25:08,742
Moving out the ecosystem a little bit, I wanted to just talk a little about how us academics

376
00:25:08,962 --> 00:25:11,643
can shift our institutional sort of politics.

377
00:25:12,064 --> 00:25:17,887
So one of the key issues of building inclusive spaces is asking yourself how open your culture

378
00:25:17,947 --> 00:25:19,047
is to marginalized folk.

379
00:25:19,667 --> 00:25:21,008
So in some ways...

380
00:25:21,994 --> 00:25:24,935
Think about how you can recruit a more diverse faculty.

381
00:25:25,235 --> 00:25:29,057
My institution, for example, has job openings that are specifically targeted at people of

382
00:25:29,097 --> 00:25:31,277
color and indigenous faculty members.

383
00:25:31,638 --> 00:25:35,839
And that's really to address some of the gaps that we have between a sort of student body

384
00:25:36,179 --> 00:25:40,401
that's sort of 60% racialized and a faculty group, which unfortunately, like me, is largely

385
00:25:40,501 --> 00:25:40,761
white.

386
00:25:41,521 --> 00:25:46,123
So we're really interested in trying to sort of push back against that type of sort of

387
00:25:46,163 --> 00:25:48,243
like dominance and against that norm.

388
00:25:49,784 --> 00:25:52,766
Think about, and this is something I heard in the presentation earlier today, think about

389
00:25:52,806 --> 00:25:53,347
scholarships.

390
00:25:53,707 --> 00:25:57,310
You know, how can you explicitly reach out to the minorities you want to attract to your

391
00:25:57,330 --> 00:25:59,372
classrooms, but it's not sufficient to just attract them.

392
00:25:59,392 --> 00:26:02,974
You have to think about the environment and the setting within which they're welcome.

393
00:26:04,035 --> 00:26:08,639
So a diverse cohort of students helps create a more inclusive learning environment.

394
00:26:08,959 --> 00:26:13,663
So when you're looking at applications, look beyond the standard requirements for entry

395
00:26:13,723 --> 00:26:14,003
level.

396
00:26:14,083 --> 00:26:16,805
It might be somebody who's interested in coming to your course who has a…

397
00:26:17,080 --> 00:26:25,648
a life experience that will enrich the cohort. So try to recruit a diverse student body in

398
00:26:25,688 --> 00:26:32,314
the same way as you would aim to recruit a diverse faculty group.

399
00:26:36,458 --> 00:26:41,142
Then thinking further up the hierarchy we have how we engage with our institutions.

400
00:26:43,632 --> 00:26:48,638
Be very vocal, if you have the privilege I have, in faculty meetings about things that

401
00:26:48,658 --> 00:26:51,461
are acceptable and unacceptable across your institution.

402
00:26:51,942 --> 00:26:57,168
We have the agency to create the environment within which we want to work, and it's our

403
00:26:57,208 --> 00:27:00,472
responsibility as faculty to create that context.

404
00:27:00,912 --> 00:27:02,874
Now, it's not that they're...

405
00:27:04,310 --> 00:27:07,633
It's not that this is ever an end, a sort of a finished game.

406
00:27:07,653 --> 00:27:10,056
It's important for me to sort of recognize

407
00:27:10,496 --> 00:27:13,239
that all of this is a process.

408
00:27:13,659 --> 00:27:16,982
So if you're having challenges within your faculty group,

409
00:27:17,002 --> 00:27:18,123
within your institution,

410
00:27:18,684 --> 00:27:20,926
opening up to more diverse approaches,

411
00:27:21,206 --> 00:27:23,128
then think about providing learning opportunities

412
00:27:23,208 --> 00:27:26,491
for your colleagues to engage with more feminist approaches.

413
00:27:27,311 --> 00:27:28,853
Make sure that you review progress.

414
00:27:29,694 --> 00:27:33,958
and measure yourself and your institution against your own targets to see how you're

415
00:27:33,978 --> 00:27:36,981
succeeding and where you're failing and then focus your attention on that.

416
00:27:37,442 --> 00:27:41,886
So we have responsibility to our students, but we also have responsibility to our institutions

417
00:27:41,946 --> 00:27:43,868
to make them safer spaces.

418
00:27:43,928 --> 00:27:47,372
There's no such thing as a safe space, but that doesn't mean that we shouldn't push towards

419
00:27:47,432 --> 00:27:48,173
safer spaces.

420
00:27:49,014 --> 00:27:52,778
So reach beyond institutional walls to build partnerships outside the institution.

421
00:27:53,163 --> 00:27:58,527
As somebody who's worked in industry and is also an academic, I would suggest that our

422
00:27:58,887 --> 00:28:06,672
student experience is enriched by that feedback in and out of our institutions.

423
00:28:06,692 --> 00:28:12,716
So volunteer, engage in community work, whether it's offering free workshops, event support,

424
00:28:12,856 --> 00:28:16,198
access to equipment or expertise, I have the privilege of equipment.

425
00:28:16,578 --> 00:28:21,101
As much as I can, I try and open up the doors to my research lab to community members to

426
00:28:21,141 --> 00:28:22,242
come and use the equipment.

427
00:28:22,871 --> 00:28:24,228
free and

428
00:28:24,634 --> 00:28:26,255
in an accessible manner as possible.

429
00:28:26,696 --> 00:28:28,977
Now that's something which benefits local community.

430
00:28:28,997 --> 00:28:31,279
Benefiting the local community benefits my students.

431
00:28:31,800 --> 00:28:35,683
So think about opening and partnering with local schools

432
00:28:35,983 --> 00:28:38,985
to offer sort of free workshops and educational initiatives

433
00:28:39,045 --> 00:28:41,087
into your sort of school settings.

434
00:28:41,107 --> 00:28:42,908
And that's something which works towards

435
00:28:43,048 --> 00:28:44,229
opening up the pipeline,

436
00:28:44,269 --> 00:28:46,411
so that you have a more diverse entry point.

437
00:28:46,771 --> 00:28:48,512
Think about how you can engage students

438
00:28:48,892 --> 00:28:50,454
in said community initiatives.

439
00:28:50,774 --> 00:28:52,475
And in some ways that sort of brings us back

440
00:28:52,555 --> 00:28:54,176
to the classroom, which is.

441
00:28:55,685 --> 00:29:00,910
Invite local developers, specifically indie developers and artists, to teach in your program

442
00:29:00,990 --> 00:29:03,412
and importantly pay them.

443
00:29:03,432 --> 00:29:10,459
It helps them survive to continue doing the wonderful work that we all celebrate here

444
00:29:10,499 --> 00:29:16,624
at events like this, but it also ensures that there's up-to-date expertise with your student

445
00:29:16,644 --> 00:29:17,485
group and student body.

446
00:29:19,310 --> 00:29:24,736
I hope that what I've done with this diagram, and I have many fewer slides and many less

447
00:29:24,796 --> 00:29:27,739
art skills than some of my sort of colleagues here, has shown how...

448
00:29:29,893 --> 00:29:35,496
how we're attempting to sort of build an ecosystem that sort of feeds into a more inclusive sort

449
00:29:35,516 --> 00:29:36,436
of classroom space.

450
00:29:36,756 --> 00:29:39,798
So I'd suggest that this can be seen as a diversity ecosystem.

451
00:29:40,418 --> 00:29:46,121
And just as I finish, I would just like to remind us all to use your privilege.

452
00:29:46,441 --> 00:29:47,081
We all have it.

453
00:29:47,201 --> 00:29:48,522
We're all privileged enough to be here.

454
00:29:48,582 --> 00:29:49,802
Think about how you can use it.

455
00:29:50,103 --> 00:29:50,403
Thank you.

