This country and many around the world are rapidly becoming drastically less safe for

482
00:31:23,276 --> 00:31:24,356
people who are different.

483
00:31:24,837 --> 00:31:29,198
Women, LGBT people, people of color, immigrants, and people of different religions.

484
00:31:29,738 --> 00:31:31,959
If that fills you with rage, good.

485
00:31:32,499 --> 00:31:34,380
Rage is how the body resists.

486
00:31:35,384 --> 00:31:37,906
Here's a quote from black feminist activist Audrey Lorde.

487
00:31:37,946 --> 00:31:41,268
She was writing in 1981, but this totally applies today.

488
00:31:41,889 --> 00:31:44,331
A well-stocked arsenal of anger is a useful tool

489
00:31:44,391 --> 00:31:47,113
against those oppressions, personal and institutional,

490
00:31:47,373 --> 00:31:49,374
which brought that anger into being.

491
00:31:50,915 --> 00:31:52,877
Okay, so the world's on fire and we're angry.

492
00:31:53,017 --> 00:31:54,538
Let's talk about games education.

493
00:31:55,435 --> 00:31:58,077
Games education is in a period of rapid growth, right?

494
00:31:58,117 --> 00:31:58,737
We know that.

495
00:31:59,158 --> 00:32:00,759
Established programs are getting bigger,

496
00:32:01,039 --> 00:32:02,881
new game programs are starting all the time.

497
00:32:03,221 --> 00:32:06,624
This is the key moment for laying the groundwork

498
00:32:06,664 --> 00:32:08,585
that will shape what games education looks like

499
00:32:08,785 --> 00:32:09,686
for decades to come.

500
00:32:10,146 --> 00:32:11,448
Here's where the ranting starts.

501
00:32:12,394 --> 00:32:17,479
So I told you this was called Teaching Students to Make Socially Aware Games, but a more fitting

502
00:32:17,539 --> 00:32:23,004
title might be something like, Video Games are Expressions of Culture, God Damn It, and

503
00:32:23,024 --> 00:32:28,730
it's ethically irresponsible of us, as educators and human beings, especially given the garbage

504
00:32:28,790 --> 00:32:34,495
fire that is politics today, to send our students out into the world without teaching them to

505
00:32:34,555 --> 00:32:35,336
think about the fact.

506
00:32:35,676 --> 00:32:39,177
that the work they produce exists in a broader social context,

507
00:32:39,457 --> 00:32:43,858
like, to seriously think about that and actually care.

508
00:32:43,878 --> 00:32:50,360
Applause

509
00:32:50,380 --> 00:32:52,861
Or, if you want a snappier title, let's just go with

510
00:32:52,981 --> 00:32:55,142
Teaching Students to Make Games Under Fascism.

511
00:32:57,222 --> 00:33:00,623
So, even with all the wonderful things that we're accomplishing

512
00:33:00,643 --> 00:33:04,325
in games education today, I want to tell you that it is not enough.

513
00:33:05,030 --> 00:33:08,271
It's not enough to produce great developers with top technical skills.

514
00:33:08,611 --> 00:33:12,832
It's not enough to graduate students with polished portfolios who land industry jobs.

515
00:33:13,132 --> 00:33:16,092
It's not enough to teach students to make games.

516
00:33:16,552 --> 00:33:18,373
They need to know that games have meaning.

517
00:33:18,953 --> 00:33:24,534
They need to learn to make games that don't just replicate all the things that are already wrong with video games, right?

518
00:33:24,894 --> 00:33:28,414
All those implicit and explicit biases that we see all around us.

519
00:33:28,914 --> 00:33:30,795
Whether our students like it or not,

520
00:33:31,215 --> 00:33:34,315
the games they make influence and are influenced by culture.

521
00:33:34,556 --> 00:33:36,034
And they need to know that.

522
00:33:37,714 --> 00:33:42,095
A lot of them have grown up in these online games cultures that perpetuate this really

523
00:33:42,155 --> 00:33:47,856
profound misconception that because video games are fun, that means they're just for

524
00:33:47,936 --> 00:33:48,176
fun.

525
00:33:49,037 --> 00:33:53,418
And they think that games exist in this apolitical vacuum and that when we think about them as

526
00:33:53,478 --> 00:33:57,659
expressions of culture, that's just for so-called social justice warriors.

527
00:33:58,439 --> 00:34:01,019
But we in this room, we know better than that.

528
00:34:01,380 --> 00:34:05,841
We know that the games that we make and our students make, it represents something that

529
00:34:05,881 --> 00:34:07,061
really matters in the world.

530
00:34:08,601 --> 00:34:12,542
And in my experience, once students enter the classroom, some of them can be shaken

531
00:34:12,583 --> 00:34:14,023
of this misconception quickly.

532
00:34:14,543 --> 00:34:18,184
Usually these are students who are women or queer people or people of color or people

533
00:34:18,224 --> 00:34:19,065
with disabilities.

534
00:34:19,425 --> 00:34:22,946
They're the students who don't have the privilege of pretending, like they don't

535
00:34:23,026 --> 00:34:24,646
see the discrimination in games.

536
00:34:25,247 --> 00:34:30,488
And they don't see how these larger forces of society and power can be a force of change,

537
00:34:30,568 --> 00:34:31,348
right, through games.

538
00:34:31,969 --> 00:34:35,150
And these are just some of my amazing USC students being amazing.

539
00:34:36,192 --> 00:34:40,916
But there are other students who respond to this idea that games and game design have social meaning with indignation.

540
00:34:41,356 --> 00:34:46,800
So I recently gave a talk to a class of first-years that included a discussion of colonialist themes in No Man's Sky.

541
00:34:48,782 --> 00:34:51,084
Two students stood up and stormed out.

542
00:34:52,485 --> 00:34:54,747
The remaining 48 engaged in a lively debate.

543
00:34:55,687 --> 00:34:57,769
So I say let those two walk out.

544
00:34:58,269 --> 00:35:04,354
Let them see that no amount of arm-crossing and dramatic groaning can bully us into sanitizing their games education.

545
00:35:05,349 --> 00:35:10,691
We have an ethical imperative to shape our students into creators who are, at the very

546
00:35:10,952 --> 00:35:14,773
least, aware of how social issues intersect with their games.

547
00:35:15,734 --> 00:35:20,156
And I'm not arguing that our students should only be making serious games or games for

548
00:35:20,216 --> 00:35:20,636
change.

549
00:35:20,656 --> 00:35:25,798
I mean, by all means, have them make cute games or strange games or even violent games.

550
00:35:25,898 --> 00:35:27,279
And this, by the way, is...

551
00:35:28,337 --> 00:35:32,179
This is a permanent exercise we did in class the day after the election, where we were

552
00:35:32,199 --> 00:35:36,562
working on self-care by making these strange, silly little sticky note comics.

553
00:35:37,462 --> 00:35:42,025
But even when students make games like that, these silly games or violent games, they need

554
00:35:42,045 --> 00:35:44,006
to be asking themselves the right questions.

555
00:35:44,426 --> 00:35:48,208
They need to ask themselves questions like, who am I representing in my game?

556
00:35:48,648 --> 00:35:50,630
What values does this game communicate?

557
00:35:51,584 --> 00:35:52,424
So here's an example.

558
00:35:52,805 --> 00:35:57,470
Three different undergraduate teams in three different programs made three different 2D

559
00:35:57,850 --> 00:36:00,693
side-scrollers and they were all in some way about gender.

560
00:36:01,414 --> 00:36:02,475
Which sounds great, right?

561
00:36:02,815 --> 00:36:07,640
So the first one is a game about navigating childhood social situations as a non-binary

562
00:36:07,680 --> 00:36:08,040
person.

563
00:36:08,961 --> 00:36:13,826
The second one is about gay men at a sit-in in 1960s Los Angeles and they're fighting

564
00:36:13,886 --> 00:36:15,108
off the police by kissing.

565
00:36:16,232 --> 00:36:20,197
And the third one, which I'm not going to show you a screenshot of, is about shooting

566
00:36:20,277 --> 00:36:24,263
women in bikinis who happen to have the faces of famous feminist authors.

567
00:36:25,725 --> 00:36:27,688
Which one of these games is not like the others?

568
00:36:28,850 --> 00:36:29,470
It's this one.

569
00:36:30,422 --> 00:36:31,022
Sorry, Corgis.

570
00:36:32,003 --> 00:36:35,904
The students who made this feminist in bikinis game, they weren't trying to be misogynistic.

571
00:36:36,144 --> 00:36:37,064
They were trying to be funny.

572
00:36:37,725 --> 00:36:40,125
In fact, on paper, they did a good job.

573
00:36:40,465 --> 00:36:43,807
And they successfully demonstrated technical skills and teamwork.

574
00:36:44,267 --> 00:36:48,568
And now, on their portfolios, when they show them to potential employers, they have a game

575
00:36:48,608 --> 00:36:50,929
that is well-developed and tone deaf as hell.

576
00:36:52,114 --> 00:36:56,457
These students needed someone to step in and say, hey, this is why this is not going to

577
00:36:56,497 --> 00:36:56,837
fly.

578
00:36:57,257 --> 00:37:00,820
They needed more courses that explicitly linked games and society.

579
00:37:01,120 --> 00:37:04,742
They needed more opportunities to practice analyzing games, not because they're going

580
00:37:04,762 --> 00:37:09,605
to go off and become scholars per se, but because they need to be better critical thinkers.

581
00:37:10,186 --> 00:37:14,969
They need to understand why they're making what they're making and what messages it sends.

582
00:37:16,130 --> 00:37:19,932
And then, if they still want to be dicks, they can be dicks on purpose.

583
00:37:21,662 --> 00:37:25,183
This is not a one-time issue or an unlikely edge case, right?

584
00:37:25,463 --> 00:37:29,284
Socially unaware games are being made in our games programs every day.

585
00:37:29,764 --> 00:37:30,704
So what can we do about it?

586
00:37:31,844 --> 00:37:33,005
First, we lead by example.

587
00:37:33,525 --> 00:37:36,005
We accept that video games are political,

588
00:37:36,365 --> 00:37:38,966
that the way that we make video games is political,

589
00:37:39,326 --> 00:37:43,447
and that the way that we teach students to make video games is political.

590
00:37:44,067 --> 00:37:46,408
That's true regardless of our personal politics

591
00:37:46,568 --> 00:37:48,228
or the personal politics of our students.

592
00:37:48,648 --> 00:37:49,788
That is just true.

593
00:37:51,106 --> 00:37:55,890
We speak candidly about the social and ethical challenges that we face in our own creative

594
00:37:55,910 --> 00:37:56,491
practices.

595
00:37:56,891 --> 00:38:00,654
We participate in the cultures of our departments and build constructive dialogue.

596
00:38:00,994 --> 00:38:05,158
We become active advocates and not just well-intentioned allies.

597
00:38:05,799 --> 00:38:11,463
So I know lots of wonderful games faculty, people who I really admire, who say, I don't

598
00:38:11,523 --> 00:38:13,345
bring politics into my classroom.

599
00:38:14,386 --> 00:38:14,766
Guess what?

600
00:38:16,050 --> 00:38:17,992
Politics are already in your classroom.

601
00:38:18,673 --> 00:38:23,457
Identity and culture and the risk of reinforcing oppression and the power to do social good,

602
00:38:23,857 --> 00:38:25,679
those are already in your classroom.

603
00:38:26,520 --> 00:38:30,483
They're in the transgender student who is too distracted to pay attention to your lesson

604
00:38:30,663 --> 00:38:31,444
on level design.

605
00:38:31,864 --> 00:38:35,966
Because they're frantically searching for information about how to get their gender legally changed

606
00:38:36,266 --> 00:38:39,567
before new anti-LGBT legislation sets in, right?

607
00:38:39,947 --> 00:38:44,489
They're the Muslim students who can't travel with your team, with their team to show off their game

608
00:38:45,189 --> 00:38:47,310
because they're afraid of being harassed by the TSA.

609
00:38:47,990 --> 00:38:49,650
Or they're in these subtler moments, right?

610
00:38:49,690 --> 00:38:54,052
Like maybe a student who's on the autism spectrum who's uncomfortable speaking out in large groups

611
00:38:54,432 --> 00:38:57,893
and can't figure out how to make themselves heard in a room full of outspoken...

612
00:39:00,035 --> 00:39:03,419
Pedagogy is one thing we can do, and it's something we can all do right now.

613
00:39:03,880 --> 00:39:06,643
We can give readings like Values at Play in digital games.

614
00:39:06,723 --> 00:39:10,387
We can assign videos from the advocacy track in the GDC vault.

615
00:39:10,627 --> 00:39:14,792
One of my students' favorites is Todd Harper's portrayals and pitfalls of fatness in games,

616
00:39:15,373 --> 00:39:17,035
to name just a few examples.

617
00:39:17,475 --> 00:39:22,817
We can share articles about how playing Pokemon Go can put black men's lives in danger, or

618
00:39:22,857 --> 00:39:28,878
about how using mental illness as a game mechanic can make for good design, but socially irresponsible

619
00:39:28,938 --> 00:39:29,598
game making.

620
00:39:30,438 --> 00:39:34,899
We can have our students play games like LIM or Assassin's Creed, which are games that

621
00:39:35,100 --> 00:39:37,660
use design to explore racial or gender passing.

622
00:39:38,597 --> 00:39:41,137
And we need to do these things like was already set up here,

623
00:39:41,337 --> 00:39:42,538
early and often.

624
00:39:43,158 --> 00:39:45,098
Teaching students to make socially aware games

625
00:39:45,238 --> 00:39:47,339
isn't a challenge that's solvable with just one

626
00:39:47,379 --> 00:39:48,739
lecture or just one course.

627
00:39:49,360 --> 00:39:50,920
The design and development of games

628
00:39:50,980 --> 00:39:53,021
can't be separated from culture, and students

629
00:39:53,061 --> 00:39:55,081
need to learn that from the very beginning.

630
00:39:55,861 --> 00:39:58,822
I know that revamping a games program or even a single course

631
00:39:58,882 --> 00:40:01,083
is difficult. I'm part of the team at UCI

632
00:40:01,143 --> 00:40:03,223
that is revamping the games major as we speak.

633
00:40:03,663 --> 00:40:06,084
And I totally recognize that sometimes we

634
00:40:06,124 --> 00:40:07,945
have to prioritize what's mission critical.

635
00:40:09,095 --> 00:40:10,675
This is mission critical.

636
00:40:11,576 --> 00:40:13,076
Our students need this.

637
00:40:13,636 --> 00:40:15,857
Socially aware students make better games.

638
00:40:16,437 --> 00:40:19,939
They make this work that they can be proud to share throughout their career because it's

639
00:40:19,979 --> 00:40:21,319
thoughtful and well informed.

640
00:40:21,839 --> 00:40:23,420
The games industry needs this.

641
00:40:23,900 --> 00:40:26,341
Our students are the next generation of developers.

642
00:40:26,741 --> 00:40:30,242
They're the ones who can bring change to video games and make them more inclusive.

643
00:40:31,418 --> 00:40:32,779
And you know what? We need this.

644
00:40:33,700 --> 00:40:38,542
There's never been a more crucial moment to train our students to be politically engaged citizens.

645
00:40:39,062 --> 00:40:43,044
They're struggling with their place in the world today, and we are struggling too.

646
00:40:43,565 --> 00:40:49,128
This is not the time to pretend like the craft of game making stands separate from those struggles.

647
00:40:50,188 --> 00:40:52,009
This is a time to get angry.

648
00:40:52,029 --> 00:40:57,852
A time to challenge our students, to empower them, and to teach them to design hope.

649
00:40:59,013 --> 00:40:59,213
Thank you.

650
00:41:09,468 --> 00:41:11,750
Well, that was awesome. Thanks, Bonnie.

651
00:41:18,636 --> 00:41:19,337
Excuse me.

652
00:41:28,131 --> 00:41:29,532
Hi, my name is Marcelo Viana.

653
00:41:30,333 --> 00:41:31,634
I am originally from Brazil,

654
00:41:32,254 --> 00:41:34,436
but I've been in California since 2002.

655
00:41:35,777 --> 00:41:38,399
Currently, I work at UC Santa Cruz

656
00:41:38,479 --> 00:41:40,641
and in the Santa Cruz County area teaching.

657
00:41:42,403 --> 00:41:43,804
And I want to talk to you today

658
00:41:43,864 --> 00:41:45,765
about why student autonomy matters.

659
00:41:47,847 --> 00:41:50,009
I want to start with a pretty basic question,

660
00:41:50,069 --> 00:41:51,230
so indulge me for a second.

661
00:41:52,731 --> 00:41:54,152
What is the purpose of education?

662
00:41:55,260 --> 00:41:57,801
We don't usually spend much time thinking about this question.

663
00:41:57,922 --> 00:42:01,504
It seems sort of broad and basic, almost silly to even consider.

664
00:42:02,284 --> 00:42:06,868
But to better address my topic, I'll need to take a step back first before we can move forward.

665
00:42:08,629 --> 00:42:11,411
To American philosopher and educator John Dewey,

666
00:42:11,611 --> 00:42:14,413
the goal of education is the creation of power of self-control.

667
00:42:14,833 --> 00:42:18,656
But by self-control, Dewey meant the ability to free oneself from external

668
00:42:18,736 --> 00:42:24,539
and more importantly internal control, the kind that our own habits of thought impose upon us.

669
00:42:25,750 --> 00:42:29,573
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. speaking in 1947 said,

670
00:42:29,753 --> 00:42:31,634
the function of education is to teach one

671
00:42:31,694 --> 00:42:33,876
to think intensively and to think critically,

672
00:42:34,396 --> 00:42:36,958
which is a widely accepted view of education.

673
00:42:38,187 --> 00:42:43,112
Brazilian educator Paulo Freire, perhaps the most influential thinker on the topic

674
00:42:43,132 --> 00:42:48,076
in the late 20th century, argued for a democratic practice of education that liberates the individual

675
00:42:48,096 --> 00:42:53,842
from all forms of domination, a process of self-actualization that empowers them to act

676
00:42:53,922 --> 00:42:55,344
upon and change the world.

677
00:42:56,698 --> 00:43:02,523
To author and educator Bell Hooks, education should develop an engaged and critical consciousness.

678
00:43:03,123 --> 00:43:08,226
To her, the role of teachers is not to merely share information, but to share in the intellectual

679
00:43:08,367 --> 00:43:09,928
and spiritual growth of our students.

680
00:43:10,868 --> 00:43:15,672
The common thread between these examples is a focus on education as a process that nurtures

681
00:43:15,752 --> 00:43:19,835
critical thinking, allowing us to better understand the world and our place in it.

682
00:43:21,106 --> 00:43:25,410
But today to say that education must foster critical thinking is a cliche.

683
00:43:25,650 --> 00:43:28,692
It is repeated so often as to be completely erased of meaning.

684
00:43:29,653 --> 00:43:33,697
It's, and when we do, it's a truism, and we take it for granted

685
00:43:33,797 --> 00:43:35,658
as if it's a self-evident truth.

686
00:43:36,339 --> 00:43:39,802
But when we do that, it loses its original power.

687
00:43:40,382 --> 00:43:44,906
To remain true, it must be constantly renewed and made integral part of our practices day

688
00:43:44,946 --> 00:43:46,307
after day, year after year.

689
00:43:47,962 --> 00:43:50,863
When we teach games, especially at high school and undergraduate levels,

690
00:43:50,923 --> 00:43:52,203
we tend to fall into this trap.

691
00:43:52,863 --> 00:43:54,504
I think we make one of two assumptions.

692
00:43:55,904 --> 00:43:58,825
One, it's not our job to worry about critical thinking.

693
00:43:59,265 --> 00:44:00,065
We just teach games.

694
00:44:00,966 --> 00:44:04,007
Or that by learning how to make games and think about games,

695
00:44:04,047 --> 00:44:06,428
our students will be able to, in the words of Dr. King,

696
00:44:06,608 --> 00:44:09,989
think intensively and think critically about the world and their place in it.

697
00:44:10,589 --> 00:44:12,870
But it might be useful to look at what he said next.

698
00:44:15,060 --> 00:44:18,602
The function of education is to teach one to think intensively and to think critically,

699
00:44:18,702 --> 00:44:23,605
but education which stops at efficiency may prove the greatest menace to society.

700
00:44:24,545 --> 00:44:28,187
The most dangerous criminal may be the man gifted with reasons but no morals.

701
00:44:28,587 --> 00:44:30,588
We must remember that intelligence is not enough.

702
00:44:31,269 --> 00:44:34,731
Intelligence plus character, that is the goal of true education.

703
00:44:35,893 --> 00:44:40,437
I wanted to revisit these ideas today because for many of us, and especially for our students,

704
00:44:40,577 --> 00:44:42,979
this is a time of crisis, of definition.

705
00:44:43,679 --> 00:44:46,602
If you teach mostly marginalized students, you know this all too well.

706
00:44:47,202 --> 00:44:50,965
This is a good time to renew our commitments and reexamine our practices.

707
00:44:51,466 --> 00:44:56,009
Instead of finding a way forward in education, our students are now stuck with a system that

708
00:44:56,390 --> 00:45:02,054
seems entirely uninterested in the formation of what Dr. King called character, what we

709
00:45:02,094 --> 00:45:03,035
might call citizenship.

710
00:45:03,675 --> 00:45:06,237
and treats education simply as a path to employment.

711
00:45:06,697 --> 00:45:08,858
Nothing more, everything else is a distraction.

712
00:45:09,598 --> 00:45:11,679
Career development is fine, people need to eat,

713
00:45:12,600 --> 00:45:15,682
but I think when we see our work in those limited terms,

714
00:45:16,042 --> 00:45:18,103
we tacitly accept an impoverished role

715
00:45:18,323 --> 00:45:19,904
and limit our students' imagination

716
00:45:20,204 --> 00:45:21,605
and constrain their possibilities.

717
00:45:22,765 --> 00:45:26,848
So if we accept a broader definition of education that includes critical thinking,

718
00:45:27,268 --> 00:45:31,130
how do we reconcile it with teaching an ever-evolving array of game-making skills,

719
00:45:31,591 --> 00:45:33,892
